#All lags are significant however as expected significance decreases as lags moves further from lag 0. As the periodcity is monthly for Addias sales Revenue data should have peaks every 12th lag. In the below chart, I see slight increase in the significantance from lag 3rd to lag 4th indicating seasonality. Also I see a pattern of every other lag value is an increase from the one prior. This was not expected but shows sales revnue from 2 quarter. Ex.data lag 0 is q1 2017 so lag 2/Q3 2016 shows an increase in significance. Overall Q1 is correlated to  previous Q1  and also previous Q3.
Acf(read.data$Revenue)

mean_forecast <- meanf(read.data$Revenue,5)
plot(mean_forecast)

#Mean forcast shows that the average is significatly below the last observation. This will not be a good forecast as the data is showing a strong increasing trend.
naive_forecast <- naive(read.data$Revenue,5)
naive_forecast
##    Point Forecast    Lo 80    Hi 80    Lo 95    Hi 95

plot(naive_forecast)

#For the Naive method the forecast chart is a straight line equal to the last observation as expected. Naive method is best for models that show no signs of seasonality or trend so it will probably not be the best method based on the ACF. Will wait for the accuracy methods to confirm.
rwf_forecast <- rwf(read.data$Revenue,5)
plot(rwf_forecast)

#As expected the random walk method with no drift is the same as the naiive method as the forecast is equal to the last observed value.
rwf_forecast_Drift <- rwf(read.data$Revenue,5, drift=TRUE)
plot(rwf_forecast_Drift)

#Random walk method with drift applies a consient growth value to the Random walk model. This leads to a linear increase to the RW/naive method. This is best for data with signs of trend and no signs of seasonality. based on the ACF this may not ne the best method but will wait for measures of accuracy 
snaive_forecast <- snaive(read.data$Revenue,5)
plot(snaive_forecast)

#Seasonal Naive method uses the value from the same quarter of the prevous year to forecast. This is a good method for data with strong seasonality. examining the Graph the forecasted value is greater the any data point from the previous year so assume there is an issue with my code/package
MA5_forecast <- ma(read.data$Revenue,order=5)
plot(MA5_forecast)

MA9_forecast <- ma(read.data$Revenue,order=9)
plot(MA9_forecast)

MA9_forecast <- ma(read.data$Revenue,order=9)
plot(MA9_forecast)

ets_forecast <- ets(read.data$Revenue)
plot(ets_forecast)
